// Each provider exposes a different reasoning knob. The DSL captures them
// in a provider-neutral way:
//
//   * `effort` — shared vocabulary (off/auto/low/medium/high/xhigh/max).
//     Claude uses it as-is; Codex clamps xhigh/max down to its own `high`
//     ceiling (see the mapping in backend/codex.rs). Values a backend
//     doesn't recognise are silently ignored.
//
//   * `extra { ... }` — provider-specific pass-through. Each `k "v"` pair
//     reaches the backend verbatim. Codex forwards them as `-c k=v` to
//     `codex exec`; Claude logs unknown keys at `tracing::debug` level
//     (the key list it consumes is documented in backend/claude_code.rs).
//
// Shared client library — provides opus, sonnet (default),
// codex-5-4 (codex:gpt-5.4), and codex-5-5 (codex:gpt-5.5). Agents below
// bind to concrete clients (`client opus`, `client codex-5-5`,
// `client sonnet`) because the script's whole point is to run two
// specific providers in parallel and have a third arbitrate convergence.
//
// To pin the codex side to an earlier snapshot, change `client codex-5-5`
// on the codex-init / codex-refine agents to `client codex-5-4`.
include "clients.gaviero"


// ── Shared configuration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// INIT_VER: the version written by the init phase; read by the first loop pass
// as PREV_ITER (iter_start 2 → PREV_ITER=1 on loop iteration 1).

vars {
    OUT_DIR  "plans"
    INIT_VER "1"
}

// ── Prompts ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Two focused prompts: one for independent initial planning, one for
// cross-model synthesis, and one for convergence judgment.
//
//   Init agents:   MODEL_NAME set per-agent; writes v{{INIT_VER}}
//   Refine agents: MODEL_NAME + PEER_NAME set per-agent; reads v{{PREV_ITER}},
//                  writes v{{ITER}} — all injected by the DSL at runtime
//   Judge agent:   reads v{{ITER}} (and optionally v{{PREV_ITER}}) and must
//                  emit `VERDICT: PASS` or `VERDICT: FAIL`

prompt init-body #"
    You are producing an independent architecture plan for:

    {{PROMPT}}

    Think from first principles. Do NOT read any existing files in {{OUT_DIR}}/.

    The plan is for a frontier AI executor that will implement it
    directly. Write in declarative, committed voice:
      - Say what to build, why, and how — nothing else.
      - Do NOT include synthesis notes, peer comparisons, rejected
        alternatives, or any meta-narrative about the planning process.
      - Commit to a design. No hedging, no "we could", no "one option is".
      - If you considered an alternative and rejected it: do NOT add an
        "Alternatives Considered" section. If the rejection implies a
        hard constraint at implementation time, inline it as a rule in
        the relevant section (e.g. "All local inference goes through
        ollama; direct ONNX is disallowed: VRAM contention."). Otherwise
        drop the alternative — the refine phase will rediscover it if
        it matters.

    The plan MUST contain (in this order, with these exact headings):
    - `## Motivation and goals`
    - `## Architecture and component breakdown`
    - `## Implementation steps` (ordered, concrete)
    - `## Data structures and API surface`
    - `## Risks and mitigations`
    - `## Operator Decisions` — forward-looking design decisions the
      executor must make at implementation time based on runtime
      observation or external constraints. Each item: one bullet,
      written as a conditional or actionable instruction (e.g. "If
      observed VRAM pressure < 4GB, set keep_alive=5m; else 0"). If
      nothing belongs here, write "None — plan is review-ready." Keep
      this list under ~10 bullets.
    - `## Phase decomposition` — partition the work into phases sized
      to land as a single reviewable PR (not per-sub-step, not
      per-whole-tier). For each phase specify:
        * owned files / crates (what this phase writes),
        * read-only dependencies (what this phase must read),
        * concrete pass/fail acceptance signals (compile, clippy lint,
          named tests, grep regressions — prefer mechanical signals
          over prose),
        * entanglement: which earlier phases' decisions must remain
          visible to this phase's executor (drives whether prior-phase
          logs must be read in full or just the gate verdicts).
      Call out when two candidate phases share enough surface that
      they should be merged rather than split.
    - `## Execution shape` — recommend either:
        (a) one `phased_plan.gaviero` loop invocation covering all
            phases, or
        (b) N separate invocations with a human review checkpoint
            between top-level items,
      and state the tradeoff explicitly (resume granularity,
      diff-review size, cross-phase entanglement, gate cost). If (a),
      specify the minimum `phase_executor.owned` scope union that the
      DSL needs (widening beyond the default template is a real cost
      — call it out). If (b), specify the natural split boundaries
      and what each invocation's `{{PROMPT}}` should carry.

    Write your plan to {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-init-v{{INIT_VER}}.md
    using clear markdown with headings.
"#

prompt refine-body #"
    You are iteratively refining an architecture plan for:

    {{PROMPT}}

    The plan file is for a frontier AI executor that will implement
    it directly and has no knowledge of the iteration history. Write
    the plan in declarative, committed voice. Hard rules — failing
    any of these makes the plan unfit for the executor:
      - Say what to build, why, and how — nothing else.
      - Do NOT write "we chose X over Y", "the previous version
        proposed Z", "this iteration adopts...", or "stronger than
        the alternative".
      - Do NOT reference peer plans, model names, version numbers
        (v{{PREV_ITER}}, v{{ITER}}), refinement passes, or synthesis
        notes anywhere in the plan file.
      - Do NOT include `## Synthesis Notes`, `## Alternatives
        Considered`, or any other iteration-metadata section in the
        plan file.
      - If a rejected alternative implies a hard implementation
        constraint, inline it as a rule in the relevant section
        ("All local inference goes through ollama; direct ONNX is
        disallowed: VRAM contention."), not as a comparison.
    All synthesis history, peer comparisons, rejected alternatives,
    convergence declarations, and version references go in the
    **summary** file (step 6) — never the plan file.

    Inputs to read:
    1. The previous pair of plans (both in full):
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-init-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md (when
           {{PREV_ITER}} = 1) or
           {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-refine-plan-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
           (when {{PREV_ITER}} >= 2).
         - The peer equivalent
           {{OUT_DIR}}/{{PEER_NAME}}-…-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md.
    2. **If {{PREV_ITER}} >= 2**, also read both prior summaries:
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-refine-summary-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{PEER_NAME}}-refine-summary-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
       Use them ONLY to focus your gap analysis: what each side
       adopted, what each deferred, what's still disputed. The
       summaries MUST NOT shape the voice or content of the new plan
       file — they are iteration metadata and they belong in the
       summary file, not the plan.

    Then:
    3. Analyse the pair. Where do the two plans agree? Where do they
       conflict? What does each miss or oversimplify?
    4. Decide whether the pair has converged. Convergence means the
       two plans agree on the core architecture, the major
       implementation steps, and the operational choices that have a
       material effect on the result. Editorial differences (wording,
       section ordering, naming, prose length) and remaining
       low-impact items listed in `## Operator Decisions` DO NOT
       block convergence.
         - **If the pair has converged**: do NOT introduce new
           structural sections, new tests, new taxonomies, or new
           operational refinements just to make visible progress.
           Copy your previous plan
           ({{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-refine-plan-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
           or {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-init-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md on
           the first refine pass) into v{{ITER}} verbatim — same
           sections, same prose, same Operator Decisions list. Byte
           stability across iterations is the desired outcome.
           Declare convergence in the summary file (step 6).
         - **If the pair has NOT converged**: synthesise a new plan
           taking the strongest elements of both and resolving
           conflicts on their merits. Make the minimum changes
           needed to close the genuine disagreements — do not invent
           additional improvements beyond what the gaps demand.
    5. Write the refined plan to
       {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-refine-plan-v{{ITER}}.md. It MUST
       contain exactly these sections, in this order, with these
       headings:
         - `## Motivation and goals`
         - `## Architecture and component breakdown`
         - `## Implementation steps`
         - `## Data structures and API surface`
         - `## Risks and mitigations`
         - `## Operator Decisions` — forward-looking design decisions
           the executor must make at implementation time based on
           runtime observation or external constraints. Each item:
           one bullet, written as a conditional or actionable
           instruction (e.g. "If observed VRAM pressure < 4GB, set
           keep_alive=5m; else 0"). If nothing belongs here, write
           "None — plan is review-ready." Carry items forward across
           iterations unless they have been resolved; cap ~10
           bullets — drop the least material if pressure builds.
         - `## Phase decomposition` — per-phase owned files/crates,
           read-only dependencies, mechanical pass/fail signals
           (compile, clippy lint, named tests, grep regressions),
           and cross-phase entanglement notes. Call out phases that
           share enough surface to be merged.
         - `## Execution shape` — recommend (a) one
           `phased_plan.gaviero` invocation or (b) N invocations with
           human checkpoints; state the tradeoff (resume granularity,
           diff-review size, cross-phase entanglement, gate cost);
           specify the required `phase_executor.owned` scope union
           (for a) or the natural split boundaries and each
           invocation's `{{PROMPT}}` (for b).
    6. Write the iteration summary to
       {{OUT_DIR}}/{{MODEL_NAME}}-refine-summary-v{{ITER}}.md. The
       summary is the deliberate home for ALL iteration metadata.
       Keep it under ~600 words. Use this structure:
         - **Convergence status** (one sentence, leads the file). If
           this version is a no-material-change convergence copy,
           say so explicitly here — e.g. "Converged with peer at
           v{{PREV_ITER}}; this version is a no-material-change
           copy." The judge keys off that phrasing. Otherwise
           summarise the remaining disagreements in one sentence.
         - **Synthesis notes**: which pair you read, what you adopted
           from each, what you changed or discarded, what you
           rejected.
         - **Alternatives considered and rejected**: design
           alternatives you weighed (different architectures,
           libraries, sequencing) with one-line rejection reasons.
           Empty if none.
         - **Operator Decisions digest**: one line per item from the
           plan's `## Operator Decisions` section, plus a note on
           whether the list grew, shrunk, or stayed the same vs
           v{{PREV_ITER}}.
       Write it for a human skimming the iteration evolution.
"#

prompt judge-body #"
    You are deciding whether two independently refined architecture plans
    have converged for:

    {{PROMPT}}

    {{ITER_EVIDENCE}}

    The digest above lists what the refine agents actually changed this
    iteration. Use it to focus your reading — if a file is not listed
    there it did not change this pass.

    Evaluate in two passes — start cheap, only escalate to the full
    plans on borderline calls. The plan files are large; reading them
    all every iteration is expensive and risks hitting the judge
    timeout.

    Pass 1 (cheap, always do this):
    1. Read {{OUT_DIR}}/claude-refine-summary-v{{ITER}}.md and
       {{OUT_DIR}}/codex-refine-summary-v{{ITER}}.md in full. Each is
       under ~600 words and carries the convergence status, synthesis
       notes, rejected alternatives, and Operator Decisions digest
       for this iteration. The plans themselves are kept deliberately
       free of this metadata.
    2. From the summaries alone, classify the iteration:
       - **Convergence shortcut — PASS**: both summaries' leading
         "Convergence status" sentence declares convergence. Look for
         phrasing like "Converged with peer at v{{PREV_ITER}}", "no
         material changes", or "this version is a no-material-change
         copy". If both refine agents agreed they are done, stop here
         and return PASS.
       - **Material divergence shortcut — FAIL**: either summary
         describes a material design change (a new or removed phase,
         a flipped major implementation choice, a different core
         architecture, a new execution shape). Stop here and return
         FAIL.
       - **Borderline**: continue to Pass 2.

    Pass 2 (deep, only on borderline):
    3. Read {{OUT_DIR}}/claude-refine-plan-v{{ITER}}.md and
       {{OUT_DIR}}/codex-refine-plan-v{{ITER}}.md in full.
    4. If you still need it, compare against v{{PREV_ITER}} to judge
       whether a specific difference is material.
    5. Return PASS if the two current plans agree on the core
       architecture and the major implementation steps. Remaining
       differences in wording, section ordering, prose length, or
       items listed under each plan's `## Operator Decisions` DO NOT
       block convergence — those are post-process work for the human
       reviewer and are expected to remain.
    6. Otherwise return FAIL.

    Output format — emit exactly one fenced JSON object as your last
    output. Keep the reason terse (one short sentence) so the response
    fits inside the judge timeout:

    ```json
    {"verdict": "pass" | "fail", "reason": "<one short sentence>"}
    ```

    A plain `VERDICT: PASS` / `VERDICT: FAIL` line is also accepted as a
    fallback, but the JSON form is preferred for machine-parseability.
"#

// ── Agents ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// Ownership uses glob patterns so each phase/model pair owns a disjoint
// filename namespace inside `{{OUT_DIR}}/`:
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<model>-init-v*.md
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<model>-refine-plan-v*.md
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<model>-refine-summary-v*.md
// The scope validator checks patterns for real overlap (see
// `gaviero_core::path_pattern`), so `claude-init-*` and `codex-init-*` are
// accepted, while collisions within a pattern are still flagged.

agent claude-init {
    vars { MODEL_NAME "claude" }
    description "Initial plan (Claude): {{PROMPT}}"
    client opus
    scope {
        owned ["{{OUT_DIR}}/claude-init-*.md"]
    }
    prompt init-body
}

agent codex-init {
    vars { MODEL_NAME "codex" }
    description "Initial plan (Codex): {{PROMPT}}"
    client codex-5-5
    scope {
        owned ["{{OUT_DIR}}/codex-init-*.md"]
    }
    prompt init-body
}

agent claude-refine {
    vars { MODEL_NAME "claude" PEER_NAME "codex" }
    description "Refine plan (Claude): {{PROMPT}}"
    client opus
    scope {
        owned     ["{{OUT_DIR}}/claude-refine-*.md"]
        read_only ["{{OUT_DIR}}/"]
    }
    prompt refine-body
    memory {
        write_ns   "plan-evolution"
        importance 0.7
        write_content #"
            Claude refinement — feature: {{PROMPT}}
        "#
    }
}

agent codex-refine {
    vars { MODEL_NAME "codex" PEER_NAME "claude" }
    description "Refine plan (Codex): {{PROMPT}}"
    client codex-5-5
    scope {
        owned     ["{{OUT_DIR}}/codex-refine-*.md"]
        read_only ["{{OUT_DIR}}/"]
    }
    prompt refine-body
    memory {
        write_ns   "plan-evolution"
        importance 0.7
        write_content #"
            Codex refinement — feature: {{PROMPT}}
        "#
    }
}

agent convergence-judge {
    description "Judge plan convergence: {{PROMPT}}"
    client sonnet
    scope {
        read_only ["{{OUT_DIR}}/"]
    }
    prompt judge-body
}

// ── Workflow ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Phase 1 (parallel): claude-init and codex-init each write an independent v1
// plan from first principles with no cross-reading.
//
// Phase 2 (loop up to x5): claude-refine and codex-refine repeatedly read the
// previous pair — full plans, plus (on iter ≥ 2) both prior summaries to focus
// gap analysis — and write a new synthesised plan (v{{ITER}}) plus a summary
// of choices made.
//
// Plan/summary contract: the plan file is for a frontier AI executor and
// contains ONLY deliverable content (motivation, architecture, steps, data
// structures, risks, operator decisions, phase decomposition, execution
// shape). No synthesis notes, no rejected alternatives, no peer references,
// no version numbers anywhere in the plan body. All iteration metadata —
// convergence status, synthesis history, rejected alternatives, operator-
// decisions digest — lives in the summary file. The refine prompt allows
// agents to declare convergence in the summary ("no material changes —
// copy v{{PREV_ITER}} verbatim"), which lets the judge's cheap summary-only
// pass PASS without reading the full plans.
//
// Post-convergence the workflow leaves both claude-refine-plan-v{N}.md and
// codex-refine-plan-v{N}.md on disk. Neither is designated canonical here
// — the human operator picks one to hand off to the executor.
//
// After each pass, convergence-judge evaluates the latest pair. The judge
// prompt does a cheap summary-only pass first and only deep-reads the full
// plans on borderline cases. Judge-control knobs (all optional; shown here
// with explicit values for documentation):
//
//   stability 2       → require 2 consecutive PASS verdicts before exiting.
//                       A single PASS is treated as provisional: the refine
//                       agents run one more pass and the judge re-evaluates.
//                       This guards against a flaky "looks good" verdict on
//                       a plan that is still materially evolving.
//   judge_timeout 180 → hard cap each judge invocation at 180s (0 disables).
//                       Wide enough that even the deep-read borderline path
//                       can finish on the largest plan files.
//   strict_judge false → an unparseable judge response is treated as FAIL
//                        rather than a hard error. A timeout on the final
//                        loop check therefore can't bury the run; the loop
//                        just exits with max_iterations exhausted and the
//                        latest pair available for human review.
//
// The judge prompt also uses `{{ITER_EVIDENCE}}`: the runtime substitutes a
// bounded digest of the refine agents' most recent summaries and modified
// files so the judge can focus on what actually changed this pass.
//
// iter_start 2: loop iteration 1 → ITER=2, PREV_ITER=1 (reads v1 init plans)
//               loop iteration 2 → ITER=3, PREV_ITER=2
//               ...
//               loop iteration 5 → ITER=6, PREV_ITER=5

workflow feature-plan-refinement {
    steps [
        claude-init
        codex-init
        loop {
            agents         [claude-refine codex-refine]
            max_iterations 5
            iter_start     2
            stability      2
            judge_timeout  180
            strict_judge   false
            until agent    convergence-judge
        }
    ]
    max_parallel 2
    memory {
        write_ns "plan-evolution"
    }
}
